  "prompt": "Why do birth control pills contain acetaminophen?",
  "response": "Birth control pills typically do **not** contain acetaminophen**. Birth control pills are hormonal contraceptives, containing synthetic versions of hormones like estrogen and progestin, which work to prevent ovulation, thicken cervical mucus, and thin the lining of the uterus to prevent pregnancy.\n\n**Acetaminophen**, on the other hand, is a pain reliever and fever reducer commonly found in medications like Tylenol. It is not a component of birth control pills. \n\nIf you are referring to a specific product or medication that combines birth control with acetaminophen, it could be a dual-purpose product designed to address both contraception and pain management (e.g., for menstrual cramps or headaches). However, such combination products are uncommon and would be explicitly labeled as containing both components.\n\nAlways check the ingredients and consult your healthcare provider or pharmacist if you have questions about your medications.",
